.SH NAME
Mooish::AttributeBuilder \- build Mooish attribute definitions with less boilerplate
.SH SYNOPSIS
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 2
\&        use Moo; # or Moose or Mouse or ...
\&        use Mooish::AttributeBuilder;
\&
\&        # this attribute is required in the constructor
\&        has param \*(Aqparam_name\*(Aq;
\&        has param \*(Aqparam_name\*(Aq => (
\&                ...
\&        );
\&
\&        # this attribute is optional in the constructor
\&        has option \*(Aqoption_name\*(Aq;
\&        has option \*(Aqoption_name\*(Aq => (
\&                ...
\&        );
\&
\&        # this attribute is not available in the constructor
\&        has field \*(Aqfield_name\*(Aq;
\&        has field \*(Aqfield_name\*(Aq => (
\&                ...
\&        );
\&
\&        # this extends parent attribute, much like: has \*(Aq+name_to_extend\*(Aq
\&        has extended \*(Aqname_to_extend\*(Aq => (
\&                ...
\&        );
.Ve
.SH DESCRIPTION
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
This module implements shortcuts and helpers for \f(CW\*(C`has\*(C'\fR keyword in Moose family of modules.
.PP
The shortcuts provided are similar to those in MooseX::Extended or
MooX::Keyword::Field, but they don\*(Aqt depend on specific OO system. Instead,
those shortcuts are just modifying option lists which are then passed to
\&\f(CW\*(C`has\*(C'\fR. This way you can use the module with any OO system which supports the
Moose set of \f(CW\*(C`has\*(C'\fR parameters.
.SH "EXPORTED FUNCTIONS"
.IX Header "EXPORTED FUNCTIONS"
All functions are exported by default.
.SS field
.IX Subsection "field"
.Vb 1
\&        has field $field_name => %more_options;
.Ve
.PP
This function produces a property that cannot be passed to the constructor:
.PP
.Vb 5
\&        has $field_name => (
\&                is => \*(Aqro\*(Aq,
\&                init_arg => undef,
\&                %more_options
\&        );
.Ve
.SS param
.IX Subsection "param"
.Vb 1
\&        has param $param_name => %more_options;
.Ve
.PP
This function produces a property that is required in the constructor:
.PP
.Vb 5
\&        has $param_name => (
\&                is => \*(Aqro\*(Aq,
\&                required => 1,
\&                %more_options
\&        );
.Ve
.SS option
.IX Subsection "option"
.Vb 1
\&        has option $option_name => %more_options;
.Ve
.PP
This function produces a property that is optional in the constructor and has a predicate:
.PP
.Vb 6
\&        has $option_name => (
\&                is => \*(Aqro\*(Aq,
\&                required => 0,
\&                predicate => "has_${option_name}",
\&                %more_options
\&        );
.Ve
.SS extended
.IX Subsection "extended"
.Vb 1
\&        has extended $name_to_extend => %more_options;
.Ve
.PP
This function does not introduce any extra hash keys, but adds a plus sign before the name:
.PP
.Vb 3
\&        has "+${name_to_extend}" => (
\&                %more_options
\&        );
.Ve
.SH SHORTCUTS
.IX Header "SHORTCUTS"
The \f(CW%more_options\fR hash can contain some shortcuts that will be expanded by
"option", "param", "field" or "extended" functions.
.SS "method name shortcuts"
.IX Subsection "method name shortcuts"
The following values:
.PP
.Vb 3
\&        1
\&        \-public
\&        \-hidden
.Ve
.PP
\&... can be passed to the following options, producing standard method names with given prefixes:
.PP
.Vb 6
\&        reader:    get_
\&        writer:    set_
\&        predicate: has_
\&        clearer:   clear_
\&        builder:   _build_
\&        trigger:   _trigger_
.Ve
.PP
The naming rules are as follows:
.IP \(bu 4
Properties starting with an underscore produce \fBhidden\fR methods when passed \f(CW1\fR (starting with underscore as well)
.Sp
.Vb 3
\&        has field \*(Aq_name\*(Aq => (
\&                reader => 1
\&        );
\&
\&        # ... becomes:
\&        has \*(Aq_name\*(Aq => (
\&                ...
\&                reader => \*(Aq_get_name\*(Aq
\&        );
.Ve
.IP \(bu 4
Properties not starting with an underscore produce \fBpublic\fR methods when passed \f(CW1\fR (not starting with underscore)
.Sp
.Vb 3
\&        has field \*(Aqname\*(Aq => (
\&                writer => 1
\&        );
\&
\&        # ... becomes:
\&        has \*(Aqname\*(Aq => (
\&                ...
\&                writer => \*(Aqset_name\*(Aq
\&        );
.Ve
.IP \(bu 4
Visibility can be forced by passing \f(CW\*(C`\-public\*(C'\fR or \f(CW\*(C`\-hidden\*(C'\fR instead of \f(CW1\fR
.Sp
.Vb 3
\&        has field \*(Aq_name\*(Aq => (
\&                predicate => \-public
\&        );
\&
\&        # ... becomes:
\&        has \*(Aq_name\*(Aq => (
\&                ...
\&                predicate => \*(Aqhas_name\*(Aq
\&        );
\&
\&
\&        has field \*(Aqname\*(Aq => (
\&                predicate => \-hidden
\&        );
\&
\&        # ... becomes:
\&        has \*(Aqname\*(Aq => (
\&                ...
\&                predicate => \*(Aq_has_name\*(Aq
\&        );
.Ve
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`builder\*(C'\fR and \f(CW\*(C`trigger\*(C'\fR are hidden by default. The only way to have them not
start with an underscore (other than passing the name explicitly) is to pass
\&\f(CW\*(C`\-public\*(C'\fR.
.Sp
These two options also don\*(Aqt change the name based on the leading underscore in
property\*(Aqs name. Builders for \f(CW\*(C`property\*(C'\fR and \f(CW\*(C`_property\*(C'\fR will by default both
be \f(CW\*(C`_build_property\*(C'\fR.
.SS "lazy + default"
.IX Subsection "lazy + default"
.Vb 1
\&        lazy => sub { return \*(Aqdefault value\*(Aq }
.Ve
.PP
\&... will be expanded to:
.PP
.Vb 2
\&        lazy => 1,
\&        default => sub { return \*(Aqdefault value\*(Aq }
.Ve
.PP
Note: this only works for anonymous subroutines.
Will not be expanded if explicit default / builder was passed (but does not take superclass default / builder into account).
.SS "lazy + builder"
.IX Subsection "lazy + builder"
.Vb 1
\&        lazy => \*(Aqbuilder_name\*(Aq
.Ve
.PP
\&... will be expanded to:
.PP
.Vb 2
\&        lazy => 1,
\&        builder => \*(Aqbuilder_name\*(Aq
.Ve
.PP
Note: passing \f(CW1\fR will work as described in "method name shortcuts".
Will not be expanded if explicit default / builder was passed (but does not take superclass default / builder into account).
.SS "isa + coerce"
.IX Subsection "isa + coerce"
.Vb 1
\&        coerce => Types::Standard::Int
.Ve
.PP
\&... will be expanded to:
.PP
.Vb 2
\&        isa => Types::Standard::Int,
\&        coerce => 1
.Ve
.PP
As long as it is a blessed reference (object).
.SS "builder / default + required"
.IX Subsection "builder / default + required"
Having a \f(CW\*(C`builder\*(C'\fR or a \f(CW\*(C`default\*(C'\fR will automatically remove \f(CW\*(C`required\*(C'\fR from the option list.
.PP
.Vb 4
\&        # will no longer be required in the constructor
\&        has param \*(Aqoptional\*(Aq => (
\&                default => undef,
\&        );
.Ve
.SS init_arg
.IX Subsection "init_arg"
\&\f(CW\*(C`init_arg\*(C'\fR can use the same shortcuts as described in "method name shortcuts".
.PP
This can be useful to turn \f(CW\*(C`_name\*(C'\fR into \f(CW\*(C`name\*(C'\fR in the constructor with the help of \f(CW\*(C`\-public\*(C'\fR:
.PP
.Vb 4
\&        # no underscore in the constructor
\&        has param \*(Aq_name\*(Aq => (
\&                init_arg => \-public,
\&        );
.Ve
.SS trigger
.IX Subsection "trigger"
In addition to shortcuts described in "method name shortcuts", \f(CW\*(C`trigger\*(C'\fR can
now be passed both as a anon sub (like \f(CW\*(C`default\*(C'\fR) or as a package sub name
(like \f(CW\*(C`builder\*(C'\fR).
.SS "use parameter value without expanding"
.IX Subsection "use parameter value without expanding"
In case you want to fall back to default behavior of some \f(CW\*(C`has\*(C'\fR parameters,
you can prepend their names with a hyphen:
.PP
.Vb 5
\&        # \*(Aqbuilder\*(Aq will be expanded, but \*(Aqwriter\*(Aq won\*(Aqt
\&        has field \*(Aqauto\*(Aq => (
\&                builder => 1,
\&                \-writer => 1,
\&        );
.Ve
.SH "CUSTOM SHORTCUTS"
.IX Header "CUSTOM SHORTCUTS"
It is possible to introduce custom shortcuts by calling \f(CW\*(C`add_shortcut\*(C'\fR:
.PP
.Vb 2
\&        use Mooish::AttributeBuilder;
\&        use Data::Dumper;
\&
\&        Mooish::AttributeBuilder::add_shortcut(sub {
\&                my ($name, %args) = @_;
\&
\&                print Dumper(\e%args);
\&
\&                return %args;
\&        });
.Ve
.PP
Each new option filter must be an anonymous subroutine that accepts
\&\f(CW\*(C`($name, %args)\*(C'\fR and returns new value for \f(CW%args\fR. \f(CW$name\fR will contain
full name of the attribute (which can be an array reference), while \f(CW%args\fR
are attribute options plus a \f(CW"_type"\fR key, which is the name of the helper,
e.g. \f(CW"param"\fR.
.PP
Custom shortcuts are called before built in shortcuts described in
"SHORTCUTS", in order of declaration. Make sure not to call \f(CW\*(C`add_shortcut\*(C'\fR
repeatedly with the same sub, as the module will not run any checks to prevent
duplication.
.PP
Example, making fields \f(CW\*(C`rw\*(C'\fR by default:
.PP
.Vb 2
\&        Mooish::AttributeBuilder::add_shortcut(sub {
\&                my ($name, %args) = @_;
\&
\&                if ($args{_type} eq \*(Aqfield\*(Aq) {
\&                        $args{is} = \*(Aqrw\*(Aq;
\&                }
\&
\&                return %args;
\&        });
.Ve
.SS "For module authors"
.IX Subsection "For module authors"
If you want to use Mooish::AttributeBuilder in your module, these custom
filters are undesirable. You want to be sure your module works regardless of
environment. In CPAN modules the module should be imported with the \f(CW\*(C`\-standard\*(C'\fR
flag, which will disable all custom behavior.
.PP
.Vb 1
\&        use Mooish::AttributeBuilder \-standard;
.Ve
.PP
This flag was added in Mooish::AttributeBuilder version \f(CW1.001\fR.
.SH CAVEATS
.IX Header "CAVEATS"
.IP "Partial support for multiple attributes per \*(Aqhas\*(Aq" 4
.IX Item "Partial support for multiple attributes per 'has'"
The module lets you write for example:
.Sp
.Vb 2
\&        has field [\*(Aqf1\*(Aq, \*(Aqf2\*(Aq] => %params;
\&        has extended [\*(Aqf3\*(Aq, \*(Aqf4\*(Aq] => %params;
.Ve
.Sp
These constructions work, but since we operate on a single \f(CW\*(C`has\*(C'\fR here,
\&\f(CW%params\fR can\*(Aqt contain shortcuts which produces method names \- that would
lead to multiple fields using same methods. The module will die with a helpful
error message if it encounters something that it can\*(Aqt handle properly.
.Sp
If you encounter this problem, you might want to
"use parameter value without expanding" to fall back to regular shortcut modules
(like MooseX::AttributeShortcuts). This module will not automatically change its
behavior to do so, so it does not surprise you.
.IP "All attributes produced are \*(Aqro\*(Aq by default" 4
.IX Item "All attributes produced are 'ro' by default"
Since the module does not depend on specific OO implementation, the only common
\&\f(CW\*(C`is =>\*(C'\fR options are \f(CW\*(C`ro\*(C'\fR and \f(CW\*(C`rw\*(C'\fR (as in base Moose). The author considers
\&\f(CW\*(C`rw\*(C'\fR to be a \fIbad idea\fR most of the time. Having one method for reading and
writing can lead to bugs that are hard to spot.
.Sp
Other than that:
.Sp
\&\f(CW\*(C`writer => \-hidden\*(C'\fR shortcut does more or less what \f(CW\*(C`rwp\*(C'\fR does.
.Sp
\&\f(CW\*(C`lazy => 1\*(C'\fR shortcut does more or less what \f(CW\*(C`lazy\*(C'\fR does.
.IP "Partial MooseX::AttributeShortcuts compatibility" 4
.IX Item "Partial MooseX::AttributeShortcuts compatibility"
The module implements many of the shortcuts from MooseX::AttributeShortcuts,
but does not aim to have 100% compatibility. Some details in overlapping
functionality may differ.
